# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mid-air-collision
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] The crash killed all 349 people on board both planes, making it the world's deadliest mid-air collision, the deadliest aviation accident without survivors, and the deadliest aviation accident ever in India.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] The final report from the investigation revealed that the Kazakh crew's failure to maintain the correct altitude led to the collision.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Contributing factors included the poor English language skills in the Kazakh cockpit, resulting in inadequate interpretation of directions provided by air traffic control, and three specific incidents of failures in crew resource management (CRM) by the Kazakh crew.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] The investigators noted the Indian airport lacked a secondary surveillance radar; the airport only had a primary radar, which produced readings of distance and bearing, but not altitude.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] The report also suggested technical enhancements (including ACAS and SSR) that would provide assistance in preventing a future crew's mistakes from being allowed to go unchecked in real time.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Saudia Flight 763 was a Boeing 747-168B, registration HZ-AIH, departing from Delhi as part of a scheduled international Delhi–Dhahran–Jeddah passenger service with 312 people on board.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] The crew on this flight consisted of Captain Khalid al-Shubaily (aged 45), First Officer Nazir Khan (aged 37), and Flight Engineer Ahmed Edrees (aged 33).
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Al-Shubaily was a veteran pilot with 9,837 flying hours.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Twelve of the crew members, including five anti-terrorism officials, were Saudi Arabian citizens.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Reports on the nationalities of the passengers of Flight 763 contain conflicting information.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] According to an article published in *The New York Times* on 13 November 1996, the passenger manifest included 17 people of other nationalities, including nine Nepalis, three Pakistanis, two Americans, one Bangladeshi, one British, and one Saudi.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] However, *The New York Times* followed up with another article, published on 14 November 1996, claiming that the passenger manifest comprised 215 Indians (many of whom were working blue-collar jobs in Saudia Arabia), 40 Nepalis, and three Americans.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Kazakhstan Airlines Flight 1907, an Ilyushin Il-76TD with registration UN-76435, was on a charter service from Şymkent International Airport to Delhi.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] The crew consisted of Captain Alexander Robertovich Cherepanov (aged 44), First Officer Ermek Kozhahmetovich Dzhangirov (aged 37), Flight Engineer Alexander Alexanderovich Chuprov (aged 50), Navigator Zhahanbek Duisenovich Aripbaev (aged 51), and Radio Operator Egor Alekseevich Repp (aged 41).
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Cherepanov was highly experienced, with 9,229 flight hours.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] A company from Kyrgyzstan chartered the flight, and the passenger manifest mostly included ethnic Russian Kyrgyz citizens planning to go shopping in India.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Thirteen Kyrgyz traders boarded the flight.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Saudia Flight 763 departed Delhi at 18:32 local time (13:02 UTC).
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Kazakhstan Airlines Flight 1907 was descending simultaneously to land at Delhi.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Both flights were controlled by approach controller V.K.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Immediately after take-off, the Saudia flight was cleared to an initial altitude of 10,000 feet (3,050 m).
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] At 18:34, Dutta cleared the Kazakh plane to descend to 15,000 feet (4,550 m) when it was 137 kilometres (74 nmi) from the beacon of the destination airport.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Two minutes later, at 18:36, Dutta cleared the Saudia plane, travelling on the same airway but in the opposite direction, to climb to 14,000 feet (4,250 m).
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] At 18:38, the Saudia crew reported reaching 14,000 feet and requested a higher level.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] At 18:39, the Kazakh flight reported having reached its assigned altitude of 15,000 feet, but it was actually higher, at 16,348 feet (5,000 m), and still descending.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] At this time, Dutta advised the flight, "Identified traffic 12 O'Clock, reciprocal, Saudia Boeing 747 at ten miles, likely to cross in another five miles.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Less than a minute later, at 18:40, the crew of a United States Air Force cargo flight made a radio call saying they had seen "a big explosion" at their two o'clock position.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Dutta attempted to contact the Saudia and Kazakh flights but received no response.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] The two aircraft had collided, with the left wing of the Kazakh flight slicing through the No.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] 1 and No.2 engines of the Saudia 747 while the left horizontal stabilizer of the 747 sliced off the vertical stabilizer (including the horizontal stabilizer) of the Kazakh flight.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] With most of its left wing and vertical stabilizer gone, the Ilyushin went into a flat spin and crashed into a field at a flat attitude near the wreckage of the Saudia plane.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] All 312 people on board Saudia Flight 763 and all 37 people on Kazakhstan Airlines Flight 1907 were killed.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] The recorder of the Saudi Arabian plane revealed the pilots said the Islamic Istighfar (forgiveness prayer) and recited the Shahada before impact with the ground.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] The collision took place about 100 kilometres (60 mi) west of Delhi.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] The wreckage of the Saudi Arabian aircraft landed near Dhani village, Bhiwani district, Haryana.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] The wreckage of the Kazakh aircraft hit the ground near Birohar village, Rohtak district, Haryana.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] The crash was investigated by the Lahoti Commission, headed by then-Delhi High Court judge Ramesh Chandra Lahoti.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Depositions were taken from the Air Traffic Controllers Guild and the two airlines.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] The flight data recorders (FDR) were decoded by Kazakhstan Airlines and Saudia under the supervision of air crash investigators in Moscow and Farnborough, England, respectively.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] The ultimate cause was held to be the failure of Kazakhstan Airlines Flight 1907's pilot to follow ATC instructions, whether due to cloud turbulence or due to communication problems.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] The commission determined that the accident had been the fault of the Kazakhstani Il-76 crew, who (according to FDR evidence) had descended from the assigned altitude of 15,000 to 14,500 feet (4,550 to 4,400 m) and subsequently 14,000 feet (4,250 m) and even lower.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] The report ascribed the cause of this serious breach in operating procedure to the lack of English language skills on the part of the Kazakhstan aircraft pilots; they were relying entirely on Radio Operator Repp for communications with the ATC.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] As part of this, the report suggested that First Officer Dzhangirov (and possibly Captain Cherepanov) might have misunderstood Dutta's final radio call, and assumed that the Saudi 747's altitude (14,000 feet) was their own assigned altitude.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Indian air controllers also complained that the Kazakhstani pilots sometimes confused their calculations because they are accustomed to using metre altitudes and kilometre distances, while most other countries use feet and nautical miles, respectively, for aerial navigation.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Although the crew in this particular collision did not appear to have made a computational error, Kazakhstan Airlines did not have enough foot-marked altimeters for all crewmembers.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Repp did not have his own flight instrumentation and had to look over the pilots' shoulders for a reading, which likely limited his own situational awareness.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Kazakh officials claimed – from the Kazakhstani plane's misleading flight data records – that the aircraft had descended while their pilots were battling turbulence inside a bank of cumulus clouds.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] However, whether or not particular crewmembers fully understood the radio transmissions or were distracted by atmospheric conditions, the five-person crew was sufficiently large that it likely struggled to maintain common situational awareness and coordinate crew actions.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Just a few seconds before impact, Repp had realised that the pilots were flying below the required 15,000 feet (4,600 m) and brought it to their attention.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Cherepanov gave orders for full throttle, and the plane climbed, only to hit the oncoming Saudi Arabian plane.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] The tail of the Kazakhstani plane clipped the left wing of the Saudi Arabian jet, severing both parts from their respective planes.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] In addition, departures and arrivals both shared a single corridor within the civilian airspace around New Delhi.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] While most areas have separate corridors – one for departures and another one for arrivals – the airspace of Delhi in 1996 had only one civilian corridor for both departures and arrivals because much of the airspace was taken by the Indian Air Force.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Moreover, neither plane was equipped with a traffic collision avoidance system, which would have alerted crew on both flights.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] The Directorate General of Civil Aviation subsequently made it mandatory for all aircraft flying in and out of India to be equipped with an airborne collision avoidance system.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] This set a worldwide precedent for mandatory use of traffic collision avoidance systems.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] As of 2021, there is an ongoing effort by the Charkhi Dadri district administration to develop a memorial honoring the victims of the mid-air collision.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] The proposed memorial, which would consist of names and other information of the victims, would be located at a to-be-built memorial park in the district.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] Miditech, a company based in Gurugram, Haryana, produced a documentary about the disaster called *Head On!*, which aired on the National Geographic Channel.
[src:mid-air-collision/1996-charkhi-dadri-mid-air-collision] The collision was also the subject of the 2009 episode "Sight Unseen", of the Canadian-made, internationally distributed documentary series *Mayday*.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] The event became known in Japan as the **Japan Airlines near miss incident above Suruga Bay** (日本航空機駿河湾上空ニアミス事故, **Nihonkōkūki surugawan jōkū niamisu jiko**).
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] The incident was attributed to errors made by air traffic controller (ATC) trainee Hideki Hachitani (蜂谷 秀樹, **Hachitani Hideki**) and trainee supervisor Yasuko Momii (籾井 康子, **Momii Yasuko**).
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] The incident caused Japanese authorities to call upon the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) to take measures to prevent similar incidents from occurring.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] The Boeing 747-446 Domestic, registered as JA8904 (First flew and Delivered to Japan Airlines in 1992), was operating Flight 907 from Tokyo Haneda International Airport to Naha Airport with 411 passengers and 16 crew.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] The flight departed Haneda airport at 15:36 local time.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] Flight 907 was commanded by 40-year-old pilot Makoto Watanabe (渡辺 誠, **Watanabe Makoto**).
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] The McDonnell Douglas DC-10-40, registered as JA8546 (First flew in 1980, and delivered to Japan Airlines in 1981), was operating Flight 958 from Gimhae International Airport to Narita International Airport with 237 passengers and 13 crew.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] Flight 958 was commanded by 45-year-old pilot Tatsuyuki Akazawa (赤沢 達幸, **Akazawa Tatsuyuki**).
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] According to the flight plan, both aircraft were supposed to pass each other while 2,000 feet (610 m) apart.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] The mid-air incident occurred as flight attendants began to serve drinks onboard Flight 907.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] JA8904's traffic collision avoidance system (TCAS) sounded 20 minutes after its departure as the jet climbed towards 39,000 feet (11,887 m).
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] The TCAS on both aircraft functioned correctly; a "CLIMB" instruction was issued to Flight 907.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] However, the flight crew received contradicting instructions from the flight controller at the Tokyo Area Control Center in Tokorozawa, Saitama Prefecture.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] Flight 907 followed an order to descend issued by the flight controller while Flight 958 descended as instructed by the TCAS, meaning that the planes remained on a collision course.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] The trainee for the aerospace sector, 26-year-old Hideki Hachitani (蜂谷 秀樹, **Hachitani Hideki**), handled ten other flights at the time of the near miss.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] Hachitani intended to tell Flight 958 to descend.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] Instead, at 15:54, he told Flight 907 to descend.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] When the trainee noticed that JAL 958 cruised at a level altitude instead of descending, the trainee asked JAL 958 to turn right; the message did not get through to the JAL 958 pilot.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] The trainee's supervisor, Yasuko Momii (籾井 康子, **Momii Yasuko**), ordered "JAL 957" to climb, intending to tell JAL 907 to climb.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] There was not a JAL flight 957 in the sky at the moment of the incident, but it can be inferred that by "957" she meant flight 907.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] The crew of Flight 907 avoided the collision by using an evasive manoeuvre once the aircraft were in visual proximity, and they passed within about 135 metres (443 ft) of each other.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] An unidentified passenger told NHK, "I have never seen a plane fly so close.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] I thought we were going to crash." Alex Turner, a passenger on Flight 907 and a student at Kadena High School, estimated that the avoidance manoeuvre lasted for two seconds.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] Seven passengers and two crew members of the 747 sustained serious injuries; additionally, 81 passengers and 10 crew members reported minor injuries.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] Some unbelted passengers, flight attendants, and drink carts hit the ceiling, dislodging some ceiling tiles.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] The manoeuvre threw one boy across four rows of seats.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] Most of the injuries to occupants consisted of bruising.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] The maneuvers broke the leg of a 54-year-old woman.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] In addition, a drink cart spilled, scalding some passengers.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] No passengers on the DC-10 sustained injuries.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] Flight 907, with the 747's cabin bearing minor damage and injuries, returned to Haneda, and made an emergency landing at 16:44.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] Flight 958 continued to Narita Airport, landing normally at 16:32.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] By 18:00 on 1 February, eight Flight 907 passengers remained hospitalized, while 22 injured passengers had been released.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] Two passengers remained hospitalized at Kamata General Hospital, while two other passengers remained hospitalized at Ichikawa No.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] In addition, the following hospitals each had one passenger remaining: Takano Hospital, Kitasato University, Horinaka Hospital, and Tokyo Rosai Hospital.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] JAL sent apology letters to the passengers on the 747; injured passengers directly received messages, and uninjured passengers received messages via the mail.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] In its report on the accident, published in July 2002, the Aircraft and Railway Accidents Investigation Commission called on the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) to make it clear that TCAS advisories should always take precedence over ATC instructions.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] A similar recommendation was made three months later by Germany's accident investigation body (the BFU) in light of the 2002 Überlingen mid-air collision.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] ICAO accepted these recommendations and amended its regulations in November 2003.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] The Tokyo Metropolitan Police Department and Ministry of Land, Infrastructure and Transport investigated the incident.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] In May 2003, Tokyo police filed an investigative report concerning Hideki Hachitani (ATC trainee), Yasuko Momii (ATC Supervisor), and Makoto Watanabe (pilot of flight 907), suspecting them of professional negligence.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] In March 2004, prosecutors indicted Hachitani and Momii for professional negligence.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] Hachitani, then 30 years old, and Momii, then 35 years old, pleaded not guilty to the charges at Tokyo District Court in 2004.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] During the same year, the lawyer for Hachitani and Momii said that the pilots of the aircraft bore the responsibility for the near miss.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] By 16 November 2005, 12 trials had been held since the initial hearing on 9 September 2004.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] The prosecution argued that the two defendants neglected to provide proper separation for the two aircraft, the instructions issued were inappropriate, and that the supervisor failed to correct the trainee.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] The defense argued that the lack of separation would not immediately have led to a near miss, that the instructions issued were appropriate, that the TCAS procedure was not proper, and that the Computer Navigation Fix (CNF) had faulty data.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] In 2006, prosecutors asked for Hachitani, then 31, to be sentenced to ten years in prison and for Momii, then 37, to be sentenced to 15 years in prison.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] On 20 March 2006, the court ruled that Hachitani and Momii were not guilty of the charge.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] The court stated that Hachitani could not have foreseen the accident and that the mixup of the flight numbers did not have a causal relationship with the accident.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] Hisaharu Yasui, the presiding judge, said that prosecuting controllers and pilots would be "unsuitable" in this case.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] The Tokyo District Public Prosecutor's Office filed an appeal with the Tokyo High Court on March 31.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] During the same year, the Japanese government agreed to pay Japan Airlines and Tokio Marine & Nichido Fire Insurance a total of ¥82.4 million to compensate for the near miss (equivalent to ¥93.6 million in 2024).
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] On 11 April 2008, on appeal, a higher court overturned the decision and found Hachitani and Momii guilty.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] The presiding judge, Masaharu Suda sentenced Hachitani, then 33, to 12 months imprisonment, and Momii, then 39, to 18 months imprisonment, with both sentences suspended for 3 years.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] The lawyers representing the controllers appealed, but the convictions were upheld on 26 October 2010, by the Supreme Court.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] The events of the incident are documented in the final season 3 episode of the Discovery Channel documentary *Aircrash Confidential*.
[src:mid-air-collision/2001-japan-airlines-mid-air-incident] The episode was first aired on 20 August 2018.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] On 1 July 2002, **BAL Bashkirian Airlines Flight 2937**, a Tupolev Tu-154 passenger jet, and **DHL International Aviation ME Flight 611**, a Boeing 757 cargo jet, collided in mid-air over Überlingen, a southern German town on Lake Constance, near the German-Swiss border.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] All of the passengers and crew aboard both planes were killed, resulting in a total death toll of 71 including 52 children.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] On 24 February 2004, Peter Nielsen, the air traffic controller on duty at the time of the collision, was murdered in an apparent act of revenge by Vitaly Kaloyev, a Russian architect whose wife and two children died in the accident.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] BAL Bashkirian Airlines flight BTC2937 was a chartered flight from Moscow, Russia, to Barcelona, Spain, carrying 60 passengers and 9 crew.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Forty-six of the passengers were Russian schoolchildren from the city of Ufa, in Bashkortostan, on a school trip organised by the local UNESCO committee to the Costa Daurada beach area of Catalonia.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Most of the parents of the children were high-ranking officials in Bashkortostan.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] One of the fathers was the head of the local UNESCO committee.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] They travelled on an overnight train to Moscow and arrived on 29 June, then, as their driver accidentally took them to the wrong airport, they missed their original flight.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] They remained there for two days until 1 July in order to find the arranged chartered flight.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Flight 2937 departed from Moscow Domodedovo Airport at 22:48 Moscow Time (18:48 UTC) bound for Barcelona International Airport (now Josep Tarradellas Barcelona–El Prat Airport).
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The aircraft was a 1995-built Tupolev Tu-154M, with aircraft registration RA-85816.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The flight was piloted by an experienced Russian crew: 52-year-old captain Alexander Mikhailovich Gross (Russian: Александр Михайлович Гросс) and 40-year-old first officer Oleg Pavlovich Grigoriev (Russian: Олег Павлович Григорьев).
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The captain had more than 12,000 flight hours (including 4,918 hours on the Tu-154) to his credit.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Grigoriev, the chief pilot of Bashkirian Airlines, had 8,500 hours of flying experience (with 4,317 hours on the Tu-154) and his task was to evaluate Captain Gross's performance throughout the flight.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Murat Akhatovich Itkulov (Russian: Мурат Ахатович Иткулов), a 41-year-old pilot with close to 7,900 flight hours (4,181 of them on the Tu-154), who was normally the first officer, did not officially serve on duty because this was the captain's assessment flight.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] DHL International Aviation ME flight 611 was a 1990-built Boeing 757-23APF in service with DHL International and registered in Bahrain as A9C-DHL.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The flight was being flown by two Bahrain-based pilots, 47-year-old British Captain Paul Phillips and 34-year-old Canadian first officer Brant Campioni, who had to fly the second leg of the journey.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Both pilots were very experienced — Phillips had logged close to 12,000 flight hours (including 4,145 hours on the 757) and Campioni had accumulated more than 6,600 flight hours, with 176 of them on the Boeing 757.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Campioni had also previously worked as an air cadet and corporal in the Canadian Military Engineers.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] At the time of the accident, the aircraft was en route from Bahrain International Airport in Manama, Bahrain, to Brussels Airport in Brussels, Belgium, with a stop at Orio al Serio Airport in Bergamo, Italy, and departed Bergamo at 23:06 CEST (21:06 UTC).
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The airspace was controlled from Zürich, Switzerland, by the Swiss federal airspace control Skyguide.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Air traffic controller Peter Nielsen, the only controller handling the airspace, was burdened with working two workstations at the same time.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] At 23:21 CEST (21:21 UTC), DHL Flight 611 reported to the area control center responsible for southern German airspace.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Flight 611 requested permission to continue the climb to flight level 360 (36,000 feet (11,000 m)) to save fuel.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Nielsen permitted Flight 611 to climb after about four to five minutes, after which Flight 611 reached the desired altitude at 23:29.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Meanwhile, Flight 2937 contacted Nielsen at 23:30, which also reported to be at flight level 360.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Nielsen acknowledged the flight, but did not assign a different altitude to either aircraft.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] That meant that both were now at the same altitude and on a collision course.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The crew of Flight 2937 disengaged the autopilot and initiated their descent at 23:35, obeying the controller instead of the TCAS.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] At about the same time, the TCAS on Flight 611 instructed the crew of that aircraft to descend.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The collision would thus not have occurred if both the aircraft's crews had obeyed the TCAS's instructions.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Flight 611's pilots followed their TCAS instructions and initiated a descent, but could not immediately inform Nielsen as he was dealing with Flight 2937.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The crew of Flight 2937, however, descended as instructed by Nielsen, contrary to the TCAS's instructions which advised the crew to climb.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Unaware of the TCAS-issued alerts, Nielsen repeated his instruction to Flight 2937 to descend, giving the crew incorrect information as to the position of the DHL plane, telling them that the plane was to the right (2 o'clock position) when it was in fact to the left (10 o'clock position).
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] About eight seconds before the collision, Flight 611's descent rate was about 12 m/s (2,400 ft/min), not quite as rapid as the 13 to 15 m/s (2,500 to 3,000 ft/min) range advised by the TCAS.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Flight 611, responding to the developing situation, increased its descent rate.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Eight seconds before the collision, Flight 2937's crew became aware of the situation when they gained visual sight of Flight 611 incoming from the left, and, two seconds before the collision, obeyed their TCAS instruction and attempted to put the aircraft into a climb.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Unfortunately, the collision had by then become inevitable — the aircraft collided at 23:35:32 CEST (21:35:32 UTC), at almost a right angle, at an altitude of 10,630 m (34,890 ft), with Flight 611's vertical stabilizer slicing completely through Flight 2937's fuselage just ahead of the wings.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Flight 2937 broke into several pieces, scattering wreckage into the Brachenreute neighborhood over a wide area.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The nose section of the aircraft fell vertically, while the tail section with the engines continued, stalled, and fell.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Many of the children's bodies fell in the field just southeast of the memorial.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Flight 611, now with 80% of its vertical stabilizer lost, entered a flat spin dive, and continued for a further 7 kilometres (4.3 mi; 3.8 nmi) for two minutes, before crashing into a wooded area close to the village of Taisersdorf at a 70° downward angle.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Each engine ended up several hundred meters away from the main wreckage after being torn from the plane due to airframe stress, causing the black boxes to stop before the plane hit the ground, and the tail section was torn from the fuselage by trees just before impact.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] All 69 people on board Flight 2937 and the two crew members on board Flight 611 died.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Only one air traffic controller (ATC), Peter Nielsen of ACC Zurich, was controlling the airspace through which the aircraft were flying.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The other controller on duty was resting in another room for the night.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] This was against Skyguide's regulations, but had been a common practice for years and was known and tolerated by management.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Maintenance work was being carried out on the main radar image processing system, which meant that the controllers were forced to use a fallback system.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Telephone systems were also under maintenance, preventing contact between other air traffic controllers.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The ground-based optical collision warning system, which would have alerted the controller to the pending collision about two minutes before it happened, had been switched off for maintenance.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] An aural short-term conflict alert warning system released a warning addressed to workstation RE SUED at 23:35:00 (32 seconds before the collision).
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] This warning was not heard by anyone present at that time, although no error in this system could be found in a subsequent technical audit; however, whether or not this audible warning is functional is not something that is technically logged.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Even if Nielsen had heard this warning, at that time finding a useful resolution order by the ATC was impossible.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] All countries involved could add additional "deviating" statements to the official report.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Bahrain, Switzerland, and Russia did submit positions that were published with the official report.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The deviating statements were published verbatim as an appendix to the report by the BFU investigators.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The statement by Bahrain, the home country of the DHL plane, mostly agrees with the findings of the report.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] It says that the report should have put less emphasis on the actions of individuals and more on the faults within Skyguide's organization and management.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Bahrain's statement also mentions the lack of crew resource management in the Tupolev's cockpit as a factor in the crash.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Russia states that the Russian pilots were unable to obey the TCAS advisory to climb; the advisory was given when they were already at 10,800 m (35,500 ft), while the controller wrongly stated conflicting traffic was above them at 11,000 m (36,000 ft).
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Also, the ATC gave the wrong position of the DHL plane (2 o'clock instead of the actual 10 o'clock).
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Russia asserts that the DHL crew had a "real possibility" to avoid a collision, since they were able to hear the conversation between the Russian crew and the controller.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Switzerland notes that the Tupolev was about 33 m (108 ft) below the flight level ordered by the Swiss controller, and still descending at 580 m/min (1,900 ft/min).
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The Swiss say that this was also a cause of the accident.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Switzerland also requested that the BFU make a formal finding that the TCAS advisories would have been useful if obeyed immediately; the BFU declined to do so.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Nielsen needed medical attention due to traumatic stress caused by the accident.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] At Skyguide, his former colleagues maintained a vase with a white rose over Nielsen's former workstation.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Skyguide, after initially having blamed the Russian pilot for the accident, accepted full responsibility and asked relatives of the victims for forgiveness.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The Broken Pearl Necklace memorial was built in memory of the incident near Brachenreute, where much of the wreckage of flight 2937 landed.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Skyguide paid compensation to the families of the dead children; the compensation amount was about CHF 30,000 – 36,000 (US$22,300 – 26,700 at the time).
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The Swiss Federal Court turned down appeals from some relatives for higher compensation in 2011.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] On 27 July 2006, a court in Konstanz decided that Germany should pay compensation to Bashkirian Airlines.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The court found that Germany was legally responsible for the actions of Skyguide.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The government appealed the ruling, but in late 2013, Bashkirian Airlines and Germany reached a tacit agreement, ending the court case before a decision on the legal issues was reached.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] In another case before the court in Konstanz, Skyguide's liability insurance is suing Bashkirian Airlines for 2.5 million euro in damages.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The case was opened in March 2008; the legal questions are expected to be difficult, as the airline has filed for bankruptcy under Russian law.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] A criminal investigation of Skyguide began in May 2004.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] On 7 August 2006, a Swiss prosecutor filed manslaughter charges against eight employees of Skyguide.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The prosecutor called for prison terms up to 15 months if found guilty.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The verdict was announced in September 2007.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Three of the four managers convicted were given suspended prison terms and the fourth was ordered to pay a fine.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Another four Skyguide employees were cleared of any wrongdoing.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Devastated by the death of his wife and two children aboard flight 2937, Vitaly Kaloyev, a Russian architect, held Peter Nielsen personally responsible for their deaths.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] He tracked down and stabbed Nielsen to death, in the presence of Nielsen's wife and three children, at his home in Kloten, near Zürich, on 24 February 2004.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The Swiss police arrested Kaloyev at a local motel shortly afterward, and in 2005, he was sentenced to eight years for manslaughter.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] However, his sentence was later reduced after a Swiss judge ruled that he had acted with diminished responsibility.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] He was released in November 2007, having spent three and a half years in prison, because his mental condition was not sufficiently considered in the initial sentence.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] In January 2008, he was appointed deputy construction minister of North Ossetia.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Kaloyev was treated as a hero back home at Vladikavkaz, and expressed no regret for his actions, instead blaming the victim for his own death.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] In 2016, Kaloyev was awarded the highest state medal by the government, the medal "To the Glory of Ossetia".
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The medal is awarded for the highest achievements, improving the living conditions of the inhabitants of the region, educating the younger generation, and maintaining law and order.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The accident raised questions as to how pilots must react when they receive conflicting orders from TCAS and ATC.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] TCAS was a relatively new technology at the time of the accident, having been mandatory in Europe since 2000.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] In responding to a TCAS RA that directs a deviation from assigned altitude, the flight crew should communicate with ATC as soon as practicable after responding to the RA.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] When the RA is removed, the flight crew should advise ATC that they are returning to their previously assigned clearance or should acknowledge any amended clearance issued.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] While TCAS is programmed to assume that both crews will promptly follow the system's instructions, the operations manual did not clearly state that TCAS should always take precedence over any ATC commands.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The manual described TCAS as "a backup to the ATC system", which could be wrongly interpreted to mean that ATC instructions have higher priority.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] This ambiguity was replicated in the Tu-154 Flight Operations Manual, which contained contradictory sections.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] On the one hand, chapter 8.18.3.4 emphasised the role of ATC and describes TCAS as an "additional aid", while chapter 8.18.3.2 forbade manoeuvres contrary to TCAS.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The BFU recommended that this ambiguity should be resolved in favor of obeying TCAS advisories even when these were in conflict with ATC instructions.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] About a year before the incident, another incident had occurred involving confusion between conflicting TCAS and ATC commands.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] In 2001, two Japanese airliners nearly collided with each other in Japanese airspace.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] One of the aircraft had received conflicting orders from TCAS and ATC; one pilot followed the instructions of TCAS, while the other did not.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] A collision was only averted because one of the pilots made evasive manoeuvres based on a visual judgment.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The aircraft missed each other by about 135 m (443 ft), and the abrupt maneuver necessary to avert disaster left 100 occupants injured on one aircraft, some seriously.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Japan published its report 11 days after the Überlingen accident, in it calling on the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) to make it clear that TCAS advisories should always take precedence over ATC instructions.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] ICAO accepted this recommendation and amended its regulations in November 2003.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Before this accident, a change proposal (CP 112) for the TCAS II system had been issued.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] This proposal would have created a "reversal" of the original warning – asking the DHL plane to climb and the Tupolev crew to descend.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] According to an analysis by Eurocontrol, this would have avoided the collision if the DHL crew had received and followed the new instructions and the Tupolev had continued to descend.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] All TCAS II equipped aircraft have been upgraded to support RA reversal.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] Additionally, an automatic downlink for TCAS, which would have alerted the controller that a TCAS advisory had been issued to the aircraft under their control, and notified them of the nature of that advisory, had not been deployed worldwide at the time of the accident.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The investigation report contains a number of recommendations concerning TCAS, calling for upgrades, better training and clearer instructions to the pilots.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] The TCAS II system was redesigned, with its ambiguous "Adjust Vertical Speed" RA voice command changed to "Level-Off", to increase proper responses from pilots.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] In the U.S. off-Broadway play *My Eyes Went Dark*, which opened 7 June 2017 and closed 2 July, playwright and director Matthew Wilkinson tells Kaloyev's story, which featured, among other characters, Declan Conlon as Kaloyev and Thusitha Jayasundera as his wife.
[src:mid-air-collision/2002-überlingen-mid-air-collision] It played at 59E59 Theaters in New York City.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] "**ABQ**" is the thirteenth and final episode of the second season of the American television crime drama series *Breaking Bad*.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] The episode aired on AMC on May 31, 2009.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] This episode introduces cleaner and hitman Mike Ehrmantraut (Jonathan Banks).
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] Along with Gus Fring and Saul Goodman, he was promoted to main cast in season three, and subsequently returned as a main character in the prequel Better Call Saul.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] Jesse Pinkman wakes from his heroin-induced sleep to find Jane Margolis dead, having choked on her own vomit.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] He frantically attempts CPR, to no avail, as she had already been dead several hours, and, in his panic, performs the procedure incorrectly.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] Horrified and distraught, Jesse contacts Walter White.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] Walt calls Saul Goodman, who sends a cleaner, Mike Ehrmantraut, to remove evidence of drugs from Jesse's apartment.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] Jane's father Donald arrives at the apartment and discovers she has died.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] Jesse blames himself for Jane's death and runs off to a crack house.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] Walt locates an anguished Jesse and attempts to comfort him, before taking him to a rehab clinic.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] Walt is preparing to undergo surgery to remove his cancer.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] The website that Walter Jr. made to bring in anonymous donations—in reality being used by Saul to launder Walt's drug money—garners media attention due to its apparent success; Walt is uncomfortable in the spotlight due to the pity shown him and his dislike of charitable donations.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] On the day of Walt's operation, as he is put under anesthesia, he groggily reveals the existence of a second cell phone he uses, making Skyler White suspicious of his activities.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] When Walt is released from the hospital, Skyler reveals that she has investigated his behavior over the past several months and found he has lied to her many times.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] Her discoveries include Gretchen never sending any money despite their medical bills nearly being paid and Walt not visiting his mother.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] Skyler then tells Walt he has to move out; Walt offers to tell her everything, but she is too afraid to know and drives away.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] Five weeks later, Donald returns to his job as an air traffic controller despite still grieving Jane's death.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] While on the job, his mind wanders to Jane when a charter plane's callsign reminds him of Jane's initials, and he inadvertently allows another plane—Wayfarer Airlines Flight 515, a Boeing 737—to cross the charter plane's path.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] Sitting beside his swimming pool, Walt is startled by an explosion overhead.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] As he watches the mid-air collision in horror, a teddy bear lands in the pool.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] The episode was written by Vince Gilligan, and directed by Adam Bernstein.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] It aired on AMC in the United States and Canada on May 31, 2009.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] The plane crash at the end of the episode was inspired by Aeroméxico Flight 498 back in 1986 (as referenced above), in which the air-traffic controller who was directing air traffic at the time of the real-life accident shares the name of the lead character of *Breaking Bad*, Walter White.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] This episode introduced the character of Mike as played by Jonathan Banks.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] The role of the cleaner to help Jesse prepare to deal with the police was originally meant to be handled by Saul Goodman, played by Bob Odenkirk.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] However, due to commitments to *How I Met Your Mother*, he was not available for filming of this episode, so Gilligan created Mike for that episode and into the next season as a cleaner.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] Club*, commented that the episode "was horrific perfection".
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] In 2019, *The Ringer* ranked "ABQ" as the 28th best out of the 62 total *Breaking Bad* episodes.
[src:mid-air-collision/abq-breaking-bad] For her work on this episode, Lynne Willingham won Outstanding Single-Camera Picture Editing for a Drama Series at the 61st Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards, while Michael Slovis was nominated for Outstanding Cinematography for a Single-Camera Series (One Hour).
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Accident analysis is generally performed in four key steps.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] OSHA combines the last two steps into a singular final step of preparing and issuing a report.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] **Fact Analysis**: After the forensic process has been completed or at least delivered some results, the facts are put together to give a "big picture." The history of the accident is reconstructed and checked for consistency and plausibility.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] This is also where the use of analysis methods can come into play.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] **Counter-measures**: In some cases, the development of counter-measures or recommendations are made to prevent further accidents of the same kind.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] The analysis step can also aid in pointing out other possible risk factors that could be mitigated during this step.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] These counter measures can be things like the implementation of controls following the hierarchy of controls.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] There exist numerous forms of Accident Analysis methods.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] These can generally be divided into four main categories which break up how and who completes the analysis.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] **Systematic Analysis** relies on using a standardized system or model for developing conclusions.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] This tends to be a rigorous effort that is performed by an expert.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] This method leaves little room for doubt and can be beneficial by ensuring expert bias does not come into play.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] **Expert Analysis** relies on the knowledge and experience of field experts.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] This form of analysis usually lacks a rigorous (formal/semiformal) methodological approach.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] This usually affects falsifiability and objectivity of analyses.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] This is of importance when conclusions are heavily disputed among experts.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] **Organizational Analysis** relies on systemic theories of organization.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Most theories imply that if a system's behavior stayed within the bounds of the ideal organization then no accidents can occur.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Organizational Analysis can be falsified and results from analyses can be checked for objectivity.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Choosing an organizational theory for accident analysis comes from the assumption that the system to be analyzed conforms to that theory.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Accident analysis breaks down the mechanisms of accidents and provides essential knowledge for the identification of hazards and justification for safety measures.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] To produce useful knowledge and avoid overlooking potential accident events, accident analysis should strive to identify as many hazardous events as possible.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Among the methods that can contribute to greater extraction of information, we can identify the Accident Anatomy (AA) method, AcciMap, Systems-Theoretic Accident Model and Processes (STAMP), and Functional Resonance Analysis Method (FRAM).
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] However, these methods have their limitations.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] The AA method and AcciMap appear to better meet the completeness requirements in the analysis.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] However, the AA method readily serves not only as a method for post-accident analysis (the analysis of multiple accident reports through post-accident analyses to assess as many recorded events as available) but also allows us to conduct predictive analysis.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] The latter analysis is carried out by identifying the deviations from operational and emergency procedures and the associated events that may lead ultimately to accidents.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] The joint use of post-accident and predictive analyses in the AA method is likely to result in increased knowledge delivery.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Many models or systems have been developed to characterise and analyse accidents.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Some of common models are similar to Hazard Analysis models.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] When used for accident analysis they are worked in reverse.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Instead of trying to identify possibly problems and ways to mitigate those problems, the models are used to find the cause of an incident that has already occurred.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Some common types of these models include the Five Why's model, Ishikawa (fishbone) diagram, the Fault Tree Analysis (FTA), or the Failure Mode and Effect Analysis (FMEA).
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] **Ishikawa Diagram**: Takes into account environmental, human, methodical, and equipment causes that can lead to a problem.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Using this model, an accident analyst could work backwards from the problem to find and mitigate potential causes.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] **Fault Tree Analysis**: Uses a tree type "yes/no" cause and effect analysis to determine potential causes of failures.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] In accident analysis it could be used to determine leading factors, post-incident.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] This model works like a flow chart to help show all processes and systems that may have effected the outcome of the incident.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] **Failure Mode and Effect Analysis**: This model uses a quantitative value to represent qualitative metrics like probability and severity.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] These values rank 1–5 with 1 being least probable or least severe and 5 being most probable or severe.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] The probability and severity values are then placed into a risk matrix to determine the overall risk.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] This can be beneficial in incident analysis by helping to determine other risk factors that could occur once an incident has happened.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Once all available data has been collected by accident scene investigators and law enforcement officers, camera matching, photogrammetry or rectification can be used to determine the exact location of physical evidence shown in the accident scene photos.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] **Photogrammetry**: Photogrammetry is used to determine the three-dimensional geometry of an object on the accident scene from the original two dimensional photos.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] The photographs can be used to extract evidence that may be lost after the accident is cleared.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Photographs from several viewpoints are imported into software like PhotoModeler.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] The forensic engineer can then choose points common to each photo.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] The software will calculate the location of each point in a three dimensional coordinate system.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] **Rectification**: Photographic rectification is also used to analyze evidence that may not have been measured at the accident scene.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Two dimensional rectification transforms a single photograph into a top-down view.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Software like PC-Rect can be used to rectify a digital photograph.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Recent advancements in technology have significantly enhanced the process of trucking collision analysis, allowing investigators to understand, prevent, and resolve accidents with greater precision and efficiency.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] These innovations provide detailed insights into the causes of accidents, help determine liability, and contribute to improving overall road safety.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] With these technological advancements, accident analysis continues to evolve, providing more precise, data-driven insights that enhance safety, streamline investigations, and support legal and insurance processes.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Human failure is categorized into two main types: errors and violations.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Errors, which are unintended actions where a worker makes an incorrect decision based on lack of knowledge or training.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Violations are intentional deviations from rules or procedures, often done with good intentions to complete a task efficiently.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] These violations typically result from poor task or equipment design, impractical procedures, or lack of understanding.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Addressing violations requires understanding why they occur, improving design, making rules more practical, and involving workers in developing safety procedures.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] To effectively manage human failure, companies should focus on identifying critical human errors, assessing performance-influencing factors (PIFs), and implementing preventive measures such as improved training and task design.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Incident investigations should go beyond blaming "operator error" and instead analyze the underlying reasons for failure.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Common pitfalls in managing human failure include assuming that workers will always detect and correct problems, relying too much on training to prevent slips and lapses, ignoring human factors in risk assessments, and underestimating the probability of human errors in safety analyses.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Employers must report a fatality within 8 hours and report hospitalizations, amputations, and eye loss within 24 hours of the incident.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] These reporting requirements apply to most private sector employers in the U.S., except for farms and government entities.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] State OSHA plans may have slightly different requirements, so employers should verify their state-specific regulations.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] When reporting, employers must provide key details such as the business name, employee(s) affected, date and time of the incident, location, a brief description, and a contact person's information.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Certain work-related vehicle accidents must be reported, particularly if they occur in a construction work zone, but incidents on public streets or while using public transportation are generally exempt.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Reporting an incident does not automatically trigger an OSHA investigation, but employers should always be prepared.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Following OSHA Standard 1904.39, maintaining accurate injury and illness records, and prioritizing workplace safety through regular safety meetings can help businesses stay compliant and improve overall safety.
[src:mid-air-collision/accident-analysis] Reading the incident reports filed by the company can provide some insight into what happened.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] From 1946 to 1989, the carrier was involved in 721 incidents.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] On the other hand, from 1995 to 2025, the carrier was involved in merely 11 incidents, out of which only 3 caused any fatalities.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] In 2013, AirlineRatings.com reported that five of the ten aircraft models involved in the highest numbers of fatal accidents were old Soviet models.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] In the Soviet Union, there was only one airline, that being Aeroflot.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Following is a list of accidents and incidents Aeroflot experienced from 1932 to the present.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] during a training flight, the aircraft entered an uncontrolled descent and crashed.
