[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Disappeared during a Khabarovsk–Troitskoye–Komsomolsk-on-Amur mail flight.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] from the mouth of the Khungari River on its left bank.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The pilot was injured in the crash, but his body was not found as it had been hidden by the hunters.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was likely found and looted; the pilot either died in the crash or was killed by hunters.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The pilot had become disorientated in strong winds and decided to make an emergency landing.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Despite a normal touchdown, the aircraft struck a hill, nosed down and crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Overturned after landing next to the runway.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The pilot had adopted an incorrect approach configuration and missed the runway.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Due to complete a Stalinabad-Khorog passenger flight.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating a Khorugh-Stalinabad passenger flight.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] An hour into the flight, the pilot got lost after entering a valley and could not locate his position.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] As night fell the pilot saw the lights of Doshtak and decided to land but the aircraft struck the side of a mountain.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The pilot had failed to use his charts properly.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating an Okha–Aleksandrovsk-Sakhalin passenger service.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Fifteen minutes into the flight, weather worsened and visibility was poor due to snow.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The pilot descended and continued along the shore.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] In the low visibility, the pilot did not realize that the aircraft was too low and while in a slight turn the aircraft crashed in an icy area in the Tatar Strait.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating a charter flight from Novgorod to Leningrad (now Saint Petersburg).
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] After takeoff the aircraft entered clouds and the pilot became disorientated and realized he was flying towards Kresttsy and not Leningrad.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Despite this, the pilot attempted to return to Novgorod, but control was lost and the aircraft crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating a Khabarovsk–Komsomolsk-on-Amur–Nizhnetambovskoye–Bogorodskoye–Nikolayevsk-on-Amur cargo flight.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The pilot attempted an emergency landing, but a wing struck the ground and the aircraft crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was due to begin a Aleksandrovsk-Sakhalin–Viakhtu–Khabarovsk passenger service.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The takeoff was delayed several times due to swells and strong winds.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The crew also noted floating logs in the water.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] That evening, when the weather cleared up, the crew decided to take off in a headwind.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] During the takeoff roll, the aircraft struck floating logs, partially tearing off both floats, nosed down and crashed in the water.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] One passenger drowned while six others were quickly rescued.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was on a special cargo flight to deliver spare parts for combine harvesters to Ukrainian farmers.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The next night, the pilot took off with full fuel tanks, two passengers and a load of spare parts.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] the pilot turned left to pass over the house where he slept the night before when the aircraft rolled to the left, struck the house and crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was completing a Stalinabad (now Dushanbe)-Kulob passenger service.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] in a nose-up attitude, then stalled and crashed and burned out.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating a Aktyubinsk (now Aktobe)-Kuybyshev (now Samara)-Moscow mail flight.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] On approach to Kuybyshev the pilot made a half-circle to reach the runway, but realized his position was incorrect.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] He began a go-around when he saw the chimney of a foundry.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] While attempting to gain altitude, the aircraft struck the chimney and crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating a Aleksandrovsk-Sakhalinsky–Nizhnetambovskoye–Khabarovsk passenger service.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The crew did not receive any weather bulletins for the route and destination before takeoff.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Several instruments, such as the variometer, path finder and artificial horizon also did not work.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Later, storms forced the pilot to descend further and eventually decided to land on the Amur River.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] On final approach the pilot noticed an island and began a sharp left turn when the left float struck the water.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft cartwheeled and crashed in the river off Malmyzh.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] and the pilot began a right turn when the aircraft stalled and crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The cause was not determined, but the pilot probably hurried his departure to allow another aircraft to depart immediately behind him.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was also flying too slow during the first turn.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Due to begin a Mineralnye Vody–Rostov-on-Don cargo flight.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating a Kulob-Stalinabad cargo flight.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The pilot circled over the airport to gain altitude and then set off for Stalinabad.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Due to unsuitable terrain, an emergency landing was not possible.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft crashed out of control in hilly terrain.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was on a training flight from Tambov to Balashov.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Some 15-20 minutes into the flight, while over Sukhotinka, the aircraft was following a road at low altitude when it entered clouds.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft rolled to the left, descended to the ground and crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating a Basargechar-Yerevan cargo flight.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] While in clouds over the Akhmangan Mountains, control was lost and the aircraft struck the side of Mount Akh-Dag.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] A search was initiated but suspended on 15 January 1937; wreckage was found on 26 August 1937.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The pilot had become disorientated while flying in clouds.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Approaching Vladivostok from the north, the pilot encountered poor weather with heavy snow.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Flying low in limited visibility, the aircraft struck two trees and crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Due to complete an Iman-Vladivostok mail service.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was being ferried from Tbilisi to Moscow for repairs.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Despite low clouds, the aircraft took off for Grozny.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Low clouds forced the pilot to fly low and just before reaching Grozny, the aircraft entered fog.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The pilot turned around to exit the fog and after leaving the fog he turned around again to fly to Mineralnye Vody, although he had permission to only fly to Grozny.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft again entered fog and was able to climb out, but the crew noticed that the instruments were failing.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Realizing that flying blind was impossible, the pilot began a gentle descent.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Distracted with monitoring instruments, the pilot did not realize that the aircraft was approaching the ground and it crashed into the top of a low ridge.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating a Uralsk-Guryev cargo flight.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Weather conditions worsened en route and the crew made an emergency landing near Kalmykovo.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] About an hour later the aircraft took off again as visibility had improved.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft never arrived at Guryev; wreckage was found near Orlik.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft as operating a training flight.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] in good weather, the aircraft began to break apart, after which it entered an uncontrolled descent and crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Collided on the runway with a PL-5 during takeoff.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The PL-5 departed the airport for Moscow.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] A few minutes later for reasons unknown, the PL-5 decided to return.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Meanwhile, the ANT-9 was preparing for the second leg of a Simferopol-Zaporozhye-Moscow passenger service.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The PL-5 then decided to land for unknown reasons without ATC permission while the ANT-9 began takeoff on the same runway, also without ATC permission.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Control was lost and the aircraft entered a dive and crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating the second leg of a Moscow-Yelets-Voronezh-Astrakhan passenger service.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Fifteen minutes after takeoff from Yelets, the engine developed problems.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The pilot descended and attempted an emergency landing in a rye field, but the aircraft struck an embankment, breaking off the landing gear and crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The engine failure was caused by failure of connecting rods on cylinders two and six due to use of too low octane fuel and the wrong oil.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Crashed after a passenger lit a cigarette in the toilet, where avgas fumes had accumulated.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating an international scheduled Prague–Cluj–Moscow passenger service.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Both aircraft were on training flights, and each aircraft had their own training zone.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Inexplicably, the pilot of CCCP-Т118 changed his heading and left his training zone, colliding with CCCP-Т190.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Both aircraft entered a dive and crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating a Kharkiv-Moscow mail flight.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Fifty minutes into the flight, the engine began to vibrate.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] A fuel smell spread through the cabin and the engine caught fire.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The pilot bailed out and the aircraft dove into the ground and crashed and burned out.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The fire was caused by a broken fuel line; this line had been previously repaired but the hose used to seal the line had been corroded by the fuel and it failed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft began to turn right and the pilot corrected it.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The pilot decided to return to Chardzhou (now Türkmenabat) and performed a left turn.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Concerned that the aircraft might not reach the airport, the pilot performed a right turn, but because the right engine was not working, this caused a loss of control.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] and crashed and burned out; the engine failure was probably caused by improper maintenance.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating a Chardzhou–Urgench passenger service.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] On approach to Kharkiv, visibility was poor due to fog, yet the crew continued the descent.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was on a test flight following repairs.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] , the crew performed a series of five turns when the aircraft rolled to the right, descended and crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The speed had dropped too much during the last turn.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] While flying north during a training flight, the crew encountered low visibility in low clouds.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The pilot saw a mountain and attempted to gain altitude, but the aircraft struck the mountain.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating a Karaganda-Balkhash mail flight.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] En route the aircraft struck the side of a mountain in thick fog.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] While approaching Shaki inbound from Yevlakh during a cargo flight, the aircraft entered fog.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The pilot decided to return but the aircraft crashed on the side of a mountain.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Spiraled out of control and crashed in the Dvina River following engine failure.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating a survey flight.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Broke up in mid-air and crashed in Lake Onega near Suisarri Island.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating a Shunga-Petrozavodsk passenger service.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Failed to lift up and overran the runway.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Due to begin a Stockholm-Saint Petersburg passenger service.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating a Kotlas-Arkhangelsk service.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] from Kotlas, the pilot flew into thunderstorms.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Instead of returning, the pilot decided to continue, but lightning began striking around him.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Disorientated and scared, he shut down the magneto and decided to make an emergency landing, but ultimately decided to continue.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] But because he shut off the magneto, the engine failed to start.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft crashed in a field and struck trees.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating a Kiev-Odessa passenger service.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Eighty-seven minutes into the flight, at cruise, the aircraft was approaching storms (which were not forecast) when the right wing failed and separated.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Before the flight, the pilot learned that weather conditions were deteriorating en route.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Despite this, the pilot took off on a Novosibirsk-Omsk cargo service.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Immediately after takeoff, the aircraft entered clouds and fog.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The pilot continued for five minutes until the aircraft crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The inexperienced pilot probably became disorientated and lost control of the aircraft.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Both aircraft were operating training flights.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] CCCP-Ш924 was following CCCP-Л956 when the first aircraft slowed down so the second aircraft could approach.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] CCCP-Л956 began a left turn when it collided with CCCP-Ш924.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft conducted several crop spraying flights in the area of Ajikabul.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The pilot allowed two passengers on board and flew some touring flights before having lunch and drinking vodka.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] He took off again and during a low pass, a horse was spooked, injuring a young boy.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] After landing, the pilot heard of this and transferred the boy to a hospital in Salyan.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] On approach, the aircraft was not aligned with the runway and a go-around was performed, but the aircraft stalled and crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating a Tbilisi–Rostov-on-Don–Moscow cargo flight.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Wreckage was found on 28 October 1938; the aircraft had drifted off course due to strong winds.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] ATC and Aeroflot were held responsible for the crash.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft took off to locate a PS-40 that had gone missing on 23 September.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] After takeoff the aircraft entered clouds, but was able to climb above the cloud layer and continue after a few minutes.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] However, surrounding mountains remained shrouded in cloud and the pilot decided to return.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Control was lost while descending through clouds and the aircraft dove into the ground and crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The crew had not checked weather conditions before takeoff.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Before returning to Grozny, the pilot invited three farmers on board for a tour.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] , the pilot began a sharp left turn when the aircraft stalled and crashed and burned out.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating the second leg of a Zaysan–Kokpekty–Semipalatinsk passenger service.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The pilot took off from Kokpekty without information about weather conditions.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] A few minutes after takeoff the pilot entered snow and decided to return, but too late.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Approaching Kokpekty the aircraft was too low; the pilot saw a hill and began turning, but the aircraft crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft took off from Sverdlovsk (now Yekaterinburg) with cargo, mail and three passengers.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Just minutes after takeoff the engine failed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The crew reduced altitude and attempted to perform an emergency landing, but the aircraft crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The engine failure was caused by a broken crankshaft due to excessive strain on the engine as the aircraft had been overloaded.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The pilot decided to return to Baku and descended, but the aircraft struck a hill and crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft entered clouds and the pilot decided to return, but during a right turn the aircraft struck the side of a mountain and crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating a Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky–Ust-Bolsheretsk mail flight, the pilot's third flight on this route.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] After passing Apacha, the weather worsened and visibility dropped to zero in heavy snow.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Despite this, the pilot attempted to land at Ust-Bolsheretsk.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] On approach, control was lost and the aircraft crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating a Grozny–Mineralnye Vody cargo flight.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] After taking off, the pilot realized that the mountains were shrouded in cloud and changed his route, flying to Gudermes and Mozdok.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Approaching Mozdok the pilot encountered low clouds and decided to return, but the aircraft struck a meteo antenna and crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] On approach to Omsk in light snow, the pilot realized that the aircraft was not aligned with the runway and performed a go-around.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] After a short circuit the pilot began a second landing attempt, but on short final the aircraft rolled left, descended and crashed near the runway.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft was operating a Arkhangelsk–Mezen–Naryan-Mar cargo service.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Approaching Mezen the crew encountered poor weather with low visibility.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The pilot was unable to establish radio contact with Mezen Airport so he asked the co-pilot to check the radio system, but the pilot became distracted in the process and lost visual reference with the horizon.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft descended until it crashed in a snowy field.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] During a mail flight in Azerbaijan, the pilot encountered poor weather.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] in poor visibility and the aircraft dove into the ground.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The inexperienced pilot may have been disorientated.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The inexperienced pilot was cleared for takeoff on a Stalinabad (now Dushanbe)-Leninabad (now Khujand) mail flight despite bad weather (thunderstorms) at Leninabad.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Control was lost on approach and the aircraft crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] , the aircraft flew into thunderstorms and became uncontrollable due to severe turbulence.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The pilot ordered the crew to bail out and the pilot jumped from the aircraft that crashed soon after.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The pilot was found alive but the two remaining crew did not bail out and did not survive.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The pilot was completing a crop spraying flight on a cotton field.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Control was lost inexplicably and the aircraft nosed down and crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The inexperienced pilot was unfamiliar with the area and should not have been flying on his own, which was against procedure.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] to Saratov after dropping off mice for a laboratory in the former city.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] Approaching Saratov the pilot encountered low visibility and flew over Saratov Airport without visual contact with the ground.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] He then turned north, but encountered snow.
[src:mid-air-collision/aeroflot-accidents-and-incidents] The aircraft entered a right turn, lost altitude and crashed.
[src:mid-air-collision/aerolíneas-argentinas-accidents-and-incidents] Aerolíneas Argentinas was established by the Argentine government in May 1949 (1949-05).
[src:mid-air-collision/aerolíneas-argentinas-accidents-and-incidents] Shortly after the carrier started revenue flights in December 1950 (1950-12) it experienced its first deadly accident, when a Douglas C-47A crashed en route to Buenos Aires from Mar del Plata, killing 17 of the 18 occupants.
[src:mid-air-collision/aerolíneas-argentinas-accidents-and-incidents] Following is a list of accidents and incidents experienced by Aerolíneas Argentinas.
[src:mid-air-collision/aerolíneas-argentinas-accidents-and-incidents] According to the Aviation Safety Network, as of July 2011 there have been 12 deadly accidents, totalling 335 fatalities.
[src:mid-air-collision/aerolíneas-argentinas-accidents-and-incidents] The deadliest accident occurred in 1961, with a death toll of 67.
[src:mid-air-collision/aerolíneas-argentinas-accidents-and-incidents] The latest accident involving fatalities took place in 1970.
[src:mid-air-collision/aerolíneas-argentinas-accidents-and-incidents] The company ranks among the safest airlines in the world.
[src:mid-air-collision/aerolíneas-argentinas-accidents-and-incidents] Aerolíneas Argentinas has written off 28 aircraft; nine Douglas C-47As, four Avro 748s, three Comet 4s, two Boeing 737s, two Douglas DC-6s, two Convair CV-240s, two Fokker F-28s, one Boeing 707, one Douglas DC-4, one Douglas C-54, and one McDonnell Douglas MD-88.
[src:mid-air-collision/mid-air-collision] In aviation, a **mid-air collision** is an accident in which two or more aircraft come into unplanned contact during flight and collide with each other.
[src:mid-air-collision/mid-air-collision] The potential for a mid-air collision is increased by miscommunication, mistrust, error in navigation, deviations from flight plans, lack of situational awareness, and the lack of collision-avoidance systems.
[src:mid-air-collision/mid-air-collision] Although a rare occurrence in general due to the vastness of open space available, collisions often happen near or at airports, where large volumes of aircraft are spaced more closely than in general flight.
[src:mid-air-collision/mid-air-collision] The deadliest mid-air collision occurred on 12 November 1996, when a Boeing 747 operated by Saudia collided with an Ilyushin IL-76 operated by Kazakhstan Airlines near Charkhi Dadri, India.
[src:mid-air-collision/mid-air-collision] The crash, in total, killed all 349 people.
[src:mid-air-collision/mid-air-collision] The first recorded collision between aircraft occurred at the "Milano Circuito Aereo Internazionale" meeting held between 24 September and 3 October 1910 in Milan, Italy.
[src:mid-air-collision/mid-air-collision] On 3 October, Frenchman René Thomas, flying the Antoinette IV monoplane, collided with British Army Captain Bertram Dickson by ramming his Farman III biplane in the rear.
[src:mid-air-collision/mid-air-collision] Both pilots survived, but Dickson was so badly injured that he never flew again.
[src:mid-air-collision/mid-air-collision] The first fatal collision occurred over La Brayelle Airfield, Douai, France, on 19 June 1912.
[src:mid-air-collision/mid-air-collision] Captain Marcel Dubois and Lieutenant Albert Peignan, both of the French Army, crashed into one another in an early-morning haze, killing both pilots.
[src:mid-air-collision/mid-air-collision] Almost all modern large aircraft (and many smaller, general aviation aircraft) are fitted with a traffic collision avoidance system (TCAS), which is designed to try to prevent mid-air collisions.
[src:mid-air-collision/mid-air-collision] The system, based on the signals from aircraft transponders, alerts pilots if a potential collision with another aircraft is imminent.
[src:mid-air-collision/mid-air-collision] Despite its limitations, it is believed to have greatly reduced mid-air collisions.
[src:mid-air-collision/mid-air-collision] On some occasions, military aircraft conducting training flights inadvertently collide with civilian aircraft.
[src:mid-air-collision/mid-air-collision] The 1958 collision between United Air Lines Flight 736 and a fighter jet, and another U.S. military/civilian crash one month later involving Capital Airlines Flight 300, hastened the signing of the Federal Aviation Act of 1958 into law.
[src:mid-air-collision/mid-air-collision] The act created the Federal Aviation Agency (later renamed the Federal Aviation Administration), and provided unified control of airspace for both civil and military flights.
[src:mid-air-collision/mid-air-collision] In 2005, in an effort to reduce such military/civilian mid-air collisions in U.S. airspace, the Air National Guard Flight Safety Division, led by Lt Col Edward Vaughan, used the disruptive solutions process to create a website called See and Avoid.
[src:mid-air-collision/mid-air-collision] One of the first mid-air collisions that happened in the United States took place at Chicago's Cicero Field on September 14, 1912.
[src:mid-air-collision/mid-air-collision] Gill had taken off before dusk in a Wright EX single-seat biplane and fellow pilot George Mestache of France, flying a Morane-Borel, had taken off after dark.
[src:mid-air-collision/mid-air-collision] Participants at this flying meet were not supposed to be in the air together after dark and during the event for night flying.
[src:mid-air-collision/mid-air-collision] Mestache ascended into the air before Gill had finished, Mestache's landing gear connected with Gill's plane causing both machines to crash.
[src:mid-air-collision/mid-air-collision] Mestache survived as did Gill initially, but Gill died on the way to the hospital.
